#Text=Eastern Bhutan
#Text=Eastern
#Text=Bhutan
#Text=is a region in Bhutan .
#Text=Cities
#Text=- a small hill-station like town
#Text=— the administrative capital of Lhuentse District - besides the dzong , not much to see .
#Text=- the administrative center
#Text=Other destinations
#Text=- a sacred valley and monastery founded by Yeshi Tsogyal and visited by Guru Rinpoche on his second visit to Bhutan - a three day walk from Khoma .
#Text=Understand

#Text=The predominant ethnic group in Eastern Bhutan are Sharchops , who are generally followers of the Nyingma tradition of Buddhism and tend to be shorter and stockier than people in other parts of the country .

#Text=Another characteristic of Eastern Bhutan is that the cities and towns are generally built on mountain slopes , a notable exception being Samdrup Jongkhar which is in a valley on the Indian border .
#Text=Lhuentse District is one of Bhutan 's remotest and least developed districts , and the landscape in the north is dominated by the Himalayas .
#Text=The district is famous for its beautiful and intricate woven cloth .
#Text=There are no shops selling it , but no doubt pieces can be bought by visiting the houses of weavers - the village of Khoma is an especially good place to look .
#Text=Talk
#Text=Sharchopkha
#Text=is the predominant language of the region , though there are local variations .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Bus from Thimphu , border crossing with India at Samdrup Jongkhar .
#Text=See
#Text=The dzong in Mongar
#Text=Aja-nye cave - AH is a sacred Buddhist symbol and nye means 100 .
#Text=The name is derived from the 100 AH symbols that miraculously appeared on the walls of the cave .
#Text=Guru Rinpoche practiced meditation here , and it is a major pilgrimage site .
#Text=Aja-nye is a one day walk from Yadi .
#Text=Yongla Gompa
#Text=is a famous monastery perched high above the village of Oron .
#Text=Bhangtar
#Text=, an area inhibited by many Bhutanese of Nepalese origin .
#Text=The clean river and wide valley offer a good place for a picnic and swimming ( though not in the rainy season ) .
#Text=The Rufous-necked Hornbill ( Aceros nipalensis ) is a common site in the district , especially around Bangtar .
#Text=Sherabtse College
#Text=.
#Text=Kanglung - the country 's highest institute of education .
#Text=Trashigang dzong
#Text=, Trashigang - a traditional dzong perched on a hill top
#Text=Chorten Kora
#Text=- an impressive stupa similar to the famous Boudhanath Stupa in Kathmandu
#Text=Do
#Text=Chorten Kora Tsechu
#Text=( festival ) , 21 Feb-7 March 2008
#Text=Buy
#Text=Woven items
#Text=from the National Women 's Weaving Center in Khaling
#Text=Cane baskets
#Text=and other cane products ( ringshu ) from Pasaphu village in Thrimshing district .
#Text=Hand made wooden bowls
#Text=( dappa ) are a wonderful and practical souvenir .
#Text=The halves of the bowl fit tighly together , so they can be used to carry cooked food , which is their function in Bhutan .
#Text=However , they also make excellent salad or cookie bowls .
#Text=Dappa
#Text=are a specialty of the Trashi Yagtse region , and it is possible to purchase them directly from the workshops of dappa makers .
#Text=Drink
#Text=The local drinks ( home-brewed ) available are ( majority)ara , singchang , bangchang
#Text=The Government 's breweries in Samdrup Jongkhar ( Eastern Bhutan ) , Gelephu ( Southern Bhutan ) and Samtse ( Southern Bhutan)are whiskey , rum , brandy and gin .
#Text=In central Bhutan , peach and apple Brandies are available too .
#Text=The beers ( made in Bhutan ) are Druk 11000 and Red Panda .
#Text=Indian drinks such as Hit Beer , Dansberg beer , Figuera red wine and Spry Red wine are also available at subsidised ( by Indian Government ) prices .
#Text=Overall , drinks are available literally everywhere with a majority of shops being " bar-shops " .
#Text=At the main hospital ( JDWNRH ) in Thimphu , Bhutan , 80 % of the deaths are attributed to alcohol ( not including collateral damages such as drunk driving , murders under the influence etc ) .
